By key question

Rankings of the 5 most important outcomes (11 respondents).

KQ 1 Expanded Preoperative Evaluation

Table 4. Among older patients anticipating surgery and anesthesia, does expanded preoperative evaluation (e.g., for frailty, cognitive impairment, functional status, or psychosocial issues) lead to improved postoperative outcomes?

KQ 2 Prehabilitation

Table 5. Among older patients anticipating surgery and anesthesia, do interventions targeted at improving physical function, cognition, and nutritional status before surgery (“prehabilitation”) improve postoperative outcomes?

KQ 3 Regional vs. General Anesthesia

Table 6. Among older patients undergoing surgery, does regional anesthesia as the primary anesthetic technique improve postoperative outcomes compared with general anesthesia?

KQ 4 Intravenous vs. Inhaled Anesthesia

Table 7. Among older patients undergoing surgery with general anesthesia, does the use of intravenous agents for maintenance of anesthesia improve postoperative outcomes compared with inhaled agents?

KQ 5 Potentially Inappropriate Medications

Table 8. Among older patients undergoing surgery and anesthesia, do commonly used potentially inappropriate medications administered during the perioperative period increase the risk of postoperative delirium or other adverse outcomes?

KQ 6 Delirium Prophylaxis

Table 9. Among older patients undergoing surgery and anesthesia, do dexmedetomidine, ketamine, ramelteon, or melatonin administered during the perioperative period decrease the risk of postoperative delirium or other adverse cognitive outcomes?

KQ 7 Lower Limb Regional Anesthesia

Table 10. Among older patients undergoing surgery, do postoperative lower limb regional anesthetic techniques, such as continuous epidural anesthesia improve postoperative outcomes?

KQ 8 Delirium Screening

Table 11. Does screening older patients for postoperative delirium in the post anesthesia care unit improve postoperative outcomes?
